4. docker run -it <image> to run interactive mode - allow us to access run and execute *container terminal* to i/p and o/p thing.
example:
🐳 Using Git Inside a Docker Container
🐳docker run -it ubuntu 
you will enter to ubuntu container terminal from your host (remote) windows cmd 
now you make new directories whatever you want to do just do it, do *exit* babes from container - so container can stop 
It creates and starts a container from the Ubuntu image and attaches my terminal to it, allowing interactive command execution inside an isolated Linux environment.
🎯
The command docker run -it ubuntu creates and starts a new container from the Ubuntu image and attaches my local terminal to the container’s STDIN and STDOUT. 
The -i flag keeps input open, and -t allocates a pseudo-terminal. This allows me to interact with the container’s shell in an isolated Linux environment.
When I type exit, the shell process stops, and since it was the main process, the container also stops.

🔥 👉 A container runs as long as its main process (PID 1) runs.
In this case:

Main process = /bin/bash
When you type: exit
Bash terminates->PID 1 stops->Container stops

⚠️ Important Clarification
If you run: 
docker run -it ubuntu -> and then inside container you create directories:
mkdir test
Those changes exist inside that container only, not on host.

Unless you use:
-v host_dir:container_dir
(volume mounting)

🚀 What If You Forget -it?
docker run ubuntu---> Container starts and exits immediately because there is no interactive terminal.
